{% block content %}
  <main>
    <h1 class="section-title">About me</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      If you've found yourself on this page, you either like running or got here by
      accident. I'm the creator of Δέσε Κορδόνια ("Tie Your Laces"), and below
      you'll learn a few things about me.
    </p>

    <section class="story">
      <div>
        <h2 class="section-title">Why I created Δέσε Κορδόνια</h2>
        <p>
          Running came into my life almost by accident — and I never let it go.
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm not a professional coach or a nutritionist. I'm a person who runs,
          reads, researches and shares what she learns. I did think about coaching
          once, but in the end programming won me over. That's how Δέσε Κορδόνια
          became my way of bringing together two things I love:
          <strong>technology and running</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Running didn't just become a hobby for me. It helped me change my habits,
          face difficulties — among them
          <a href="post-trexsimo-imikranies-en.html">my migraines</a> — and see
          everyday life with more optimism. I wanted to share that experience with
          more people — and that's how this website was born. If I manage to inspire
          someone even a little through it, this page has achieved its goal.
        </p>
        <p>
          There's one more reason I created this page. I too was once a person
          searching for reliable information to improve as a runner without having to
          pay a coach. Since running is a hobby for me and not a profession, I wanted
          to build a place where that information is free and easy to access.
        </p>
      </div>
      <picture>
        <source type="image/avif" srcset="images/cat-desekordonia.avif?v=1">
        <source type="image/webp" srcset="images/cat-desekordonia.webp?v=1">
        <img src="images/cat-desekordonia.jpg?v=1" alt="A girl tying her laces on the track at sunset" loading="lazy" decoding="async">
      </picture>
    </section>

    <div class="recap about-recap">
      <h4><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M2 3h6a4 4 0 0 1 4 4v14a3 3 0 0 0-3-3H2z"/><path d="M22 3h-6a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v14a3 3 0 0 1 3-3h7z"/></svg> How I work</h4>
      <p>
        Before any article is published, I spend time reading scientific studies,
        guidelines from international organisations and reliable sources. I try to
        turn that information into something simple, understandable and useful for
        every runner. At the end of the more scientific articles you'll find the
        main sources I used — so you can check them for yourself.
      </p>
      <p>
        Still, the content of this site doesn't replace the advice of a health
        professional or a coach.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="contact-card">
      <span class="contact-icon"><svg style="width:1.5rem;height:1.5rem;color:var(--accent)" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M21 15a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H7l-4 4V5a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h14a2 2 0 0 1 2 2z"/></svg></span>
      <h3>Let's keep in touch</h3>
      <p>
        A question, an idea or an article suggestion? Send me an email — I'd love
        to read it!
      </p>
      <a class="btn" href="mailto:hello@desekordonia.com">hello@desekordonia.com</a>
    </div>

    <p class="about-closing">
      I hope Δέσε Κορδόνια becomes the nudge for you to take your own next step in
      running — whatever that step may be.
    </p>
  </main>
{% endblock %}

